<p>Let's deal with that in a second - and do something cool first. So, remember
how some of the <code>app/console</code> commands have really pretty colored text when
they print? Well, we're not inside a console command in PHPUnit, but I'd
<em>love</em> to be able to print out with colors.</p>
<p>Good news! It turns out, this is really easy. The class that handles the
styling is called <code>ConsoleOutput</code>, and you can use it directly from anywhere.</p>
<p>Start by adding a <code>private $output</code> property that we'll use to avoid creating
a bunch of these objects. Then down in <code>printDebug()</code>, say
<code>if ($this-&gt;output === null)</code> then <code>$this-&gt;output = new ConsoleOutput();</code>.
This is the <code>$output</code> variable you're passed in a normal Symfony command.
This means we can say <code>$this-&gt;output-&gt;writeln()</code> and pass it the <code>$string</code>:</p>
<p><div class="code-block-wrapper" data-code-block-guid="6ab4843e77">
